name: n-hexyl acetate
Reason: 1,3-dioxolane has a melting point of -106.0 degrees Celsius. The introduction of the n-hexyl group (C6H13) in place of a hydrogen atom increases the molecular weight and size which generally raises the melting point. The acetate group introduces a carbonyl functional group, which can participate in hydrogen bonding and rigidify the structure, estimated at around +20. The n-hexyl group also introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions and potentially hydrogen bonding, further raising the melting point by about +30.
